      <memberdef kind="function" id="group__adaptors_1ga0ece82019efe58d95672f13d3f7c2034" prot="public" static="no" const="no" explicit="no" inline="no" virt="non-virtual">
        <templateparamlist>
          <param>
            <type>class T1</type>
          </param>
          <param>
            <type>class T2</type>
          </param>
        </templateparamlist>
        <type>auto</type>
        <definition>auto futures::operator&amp;&amp;</definition>
        <argsstring>(T1 &amp;&amp;lhs, T2 &amp;&amp;rhs)</argsstring>
        <name>operator&amp;&amp;</name>
        <param>
          <type>T1 &amp;&amp;</type>
          <declname>lhs</declname>
        </param>
        <param>
          <type>T2 &amp;&amp;</type>
          <declname>rhs</declname>
        </param>
        <briefdescription>
<para>Operator to create a future object that becomes ready when all of the input futures are ready. </para>
        </briefdescription>
        <detaileddescription>
<para>Operator&amp;&amp; works for futures and functions (which are converted to futures with the default executor) If the future is a <ref refid="classfutures_1_1when__all__future" kindref="compound">when_all_future</ref> itself, then it gets merged instead of becoming a child future of another <ref refid="classfutures_1_1when__all__future" kindref="compound">when_all_future</ref>.</para>
<para>When the user asks for f1 &amp;&amp; f2 &amp;&amp; f3, we want that to return a single future that waits for &lt;f1,f2,f3&gt; rather than a future that wait for two futures &lt;f1,&lt;f2,f3&gt;&gt;.</para>
<para>This emulates the usual behavior we expect from other types with operator&amp;&amp;.</para>
<para>Note that this default behaviour is different from when_all(...), which doesn&apos;t merge the <ref refid="classfutures_1_1when__all__future" kindref="compound">when_all_future</ref> objects by default, because they are variadic functions and this intention can be controlled explicitly:<itemizedlist>
<listitem><para>when_all(f1,f2,f3) -&gt; &lt;f1,f2,f3&gt;</para>
</listitem><listitem><para>when_all(f1,when_all(f2,f3)) -&gt; &lt;f1,&lt;f2,f3&gt;&gt;</para>
</listitem></itemizedlist>
</para>
<para><simplesect kind="return"><para><ref refid="classfutures_1_1when__all__future" kindref="compound">when_all_future</ref> object that concatenates all futures </para>
</simplesect>
</para>
        </detaileddescription>
        <inbodydescription>
